%% Figure 5: Cross-organisation audit via capability receipts (§7.5)
%%
%% A regulator audits a bank's AI agent activity over a period, using only
%% the bank's published cryptographic artefacts. No on-premise inspection;
%% no shared secret with the bank's AI vendor; no contact required with
%% any third party at verification time.

sequenceDiagram
    autonumber
    participant Bank as Bank AI Agent
    participant Gate as Bank's<br/>VCD Gate
    participant Audit as Bank's Audit<br/>(Merkle-chained log)
    participant Bank_KEY as Bank's published<br/>issuer key + policy registry<br/>+ Lean development
    participant FCA as FCA Examiner

    Note over Bank,Gate: One quarter of agent activity
    Bank->>Gate: tool call (transfer, args)
    Gate->>Gate: verify token, schema, policy
    Gate->>Audit: emit signed receipt
    Note over Audit: ... thousands of receipts ...

    Note over Bank_KEY: Bank publishes<br/>(out-of-band, signed)<br/>once

    FCA->>Audit: request quarterly receipt log
    Audit-->>FCA: signed Merkle root +<br/>receipt batch
    FCA->>Bank_KEY: fetch published key,<br/>policy registry,<br/>Lean theorems
    Bank_KEY-->>FCA: artefacts (verifiable offline)

    Note over FCA: For each receipt:
    Note over FCA: ① verify signature against published key
    Note over FCA: ② check schema_hash against registry
    Note over FCA: ③ check policy_proof_hash against registry
    Note over FCA: ④ rebuild Lean development, confirm cited theorem closes
    Note over FCA: ⑤ confirm call_args_hash satisfies cited policy

    Note over FCA: Audit conclusion is a deterministic<br/>function of published artefacts —<br/>no information asymmetry remains.
